<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-641  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 641.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 10 1990 v36 n1826 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Component, tester vendors move on boundary scan tech. (integratedcircuit design testing using the boundary scan technology)(Spotlight on ATE)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dunn, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ratification of the IEEE 1149.1 bus standard will likely increaseuse of the boundary scan technology for testing integrated circuitdesigns.andP;  As circuit boards get denser and smaller and use moresurface-mount and tape-bonded components, traditional'bed-of-nails' testers cannot access component input and outputpins for functional and in-circuit tests.andP;  The presence of specialdata registers allows the chips to be linked together to form aspecial test circuit, or scan path.andP;  Serialized data is sent intothe circuit, and the resulting output is read to assure that theICs are connected properly; some problems can be diagnosed aswell.andP;  High-quality test software is required in addition to thespecial data registers, which makes what may appear to be a simpleprocess much more confusing.andP;  Boundary scan software from TeradyneInc, GenRad Inc, Hewlett-Packard Co and Texas Instruments isdescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Automatic Test EquipmentCircuit DesignTestingNew TechniqueManufacturersIntegrated circuitsSoftware packagesComputer-aided design.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   In-circuit test can be performed using a mix of real and virtualchannels. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>